Yes, the color string seems quite strange.

In this use case, the output  we are printing is not controlled by us, it's from the compile output of a child process, and it includes both warning and error. It seems a bit difficult and not necessary to seperate them into warnings and errors. all I just want to do is to highlight it. If we use console-debug's error mechanism, we will mark an original warning as an error, which may seem a bit confused. So I thins maybe we can use 'colors' module, which can be used like:

```
var colors = require('colors');

console.log("The style of this text will be modified".black);
console.log("The style of this text will be modified".red);
```

@robertnishihara I think we can just ignore the failure assuming the proper functioning of Ray applications do not depend on this write operation. I think this is true since we're just removing objects from the object store.

Note that the `ReleaseSender` method just releases the connection from the connection pool. We'll need a method similar to `RemoveReceiver`, which, in addition to removing the connection from the sender connection maps, will also need to remove connections from the `available_*` sender maps. Once connections are no longer referenced, I expect them to be closed (we ought to confirm via asio documentation), but it might make sense to invoke close explicitly so that any subsequent attempt to use the connection fails. If we close the connection explicitly, we might want to hint at such semantics by naming the method something like `DestroySender` or `RemoveAndCloseSender`.

We could simplify the connection pool API by converting the `RemoveReceiver` method to a `RemoveConnection` method; the lookups required to figure out connection type etc. are cheap.
